node.text: Sopes are rounds of griddled masa with a little rim around the edge to hold delicious fillings. “In my house, sopes were always filled with refried black beans, pulled chicken, chopped romaine lettuce, crema, crumbled fresh cheese, and then one or two salsas and guacamole or avocado to top,” writes Epi contributor @Fanygerson. But sopes are made to be customized, she says. Learn the cooking method in the video above, and check out the link in our bio to get the recipe.

node.text: Gorditas are one of the most popular street foods in Mexico. According to @fanygerson, the translation means “little fatties,” and they’re thick masa pockets that are toasted on a comal, then stuffed with fillings. Watch the video to learn all of Gerson’s tips and tricks, then click the link in our bio for the recipe—and a sweet variation, too.

node.text: You can find tlacoyos all across Mexico—and they’re one of @fanygerson’s favorite street food snacks. The thick oval-shaped masa patties are crispy on the outside, stuffed with beans or other fillings, and piled high with a refreshing cactus salad. Here, Fany shows you how to make them, step by step, to devour right away or stock your freezer. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: “For many families, making tamales is a ritual, and younger and older generations each have specific roles in the process,” writes Epi contributor, chef @fanygerson. Here, Gerson walks you through the whole method, step by step, so you can make the fluffiest, most flavorful tamales of your life. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio.

node.text: When chef and cookbook author Fany Gerson (@fanygerson) first moved to New York from Mexico over 20 years ago, it wasn’t a matter of *wanting* to find good tortillas—she *needed* them. Mass-produced tortillas from supermarkets and delis had nothing in common with the supple, fragrant fresh tortillas she knew and loved in Mexico. So she started making her own—now she’s here to share her tips, step by step. Read more and get the recipe at the link in our bio. Director: @c.emanuelsmith DP: @bendewster Editor: @elliottjchrist

node.text: One day, you will be in a market, and you will pass the coconuts. They will grab your attention. You'll say to yourself, "I'm going to buy this coconut." You settle at the register, and bring your groceries home. You put most of them away. As you hold up that last item, you will ask yourself: "Why did I buy this coconut?" At least we can help answer how to open it!

node.title: 50 People Try to Crack Open a Coconut

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 19, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: The problem: You want a tasty homemade treat, but don't want to spend hours in the kitchen. The solution: Epi's collection of 57 easy baking recipes that are satisfying without being too complicated. A slice of mochi cake, a peanut butter cookie, or a savory Dutch baby are all within reach! Just follow the link in bio and you’ll be baking in no-time. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 19, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Keep it simple tonight. Epi has 111 easy recipes to help you get dinner on the table with minimal effort. Speedy seared scallops (we’re talking four minutes), sheet pan bakes, and filling salads like this one are just a click away. So kick up your feet, check out the link in bio, and relax. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 18, 2021. May be an image of dessert.

node.text: When cherries are at their peak, pie is just the beginning. Bursting with flavor, this ruby red fruit is prime for cobblers, clafoutis, and cocktails. Try it savory! Toss cherries with grilled beets and burrata for a different take on that classic cheese and fruit combo. Pop over to the link in bio for 59 of Epi's favorite cherry recipes. Photo @yungbludlau, Food Styling @heysueli

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person, food and indoor.

node.text: Call it staycation cuisine: These recipes will transport your tastebuds, even if you're stuck at home. Steam some clams with sweet corn for beach cookout vibes. Pile platters with summery salads packed with peak-season fruits and veggies. And don’t forget the dessert. Check out the link in bio for menu inspo. Photo @yungbludlau, Food Styling @susietheodorou, Prop Styling @emilyeisen

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food and drink.

node.text: Owning a shaved ice maker may feel ridiculously over-the-top. There's no doubt this machine is an investment in money and space, but consider this: Once you have a shaved ice maker, there’s nothing to stop you from inviting friends over all summer to make vibrant layered desserts. Check out the link in bio for @kendrakendrakendra’s tips on hosting a shaved ice party. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @kendrakendrakendra

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 16, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Cobblers. Crisps. Compotes. Peaches at their prime don’t need much to become a show-stopping dessert. Now's the time to work this extraordinarily versatile stone fruit into your galettes, ice creams, shortcakes, parfaits, panna cotta, and more. Get some recipe inspo at the link in bio. Photo @christophertestani

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 15, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: This jerk-spiced grilled tofu is perfect for a backyard dinner party, according to Epi contributor Chrissy Tracey (@eatwithchrissy). Packed with spicy, warm, and gently sweet flavors, Tracey's tofu soaks up a vibrant jerk marinade before it hits the grill. (If you have time, drain, press, and freeze your tofu beforehand—it's worth it for the ultimate texture.) Pair with sweet, ripe plantains and a quick-and-easy mango salsa. Get the recipe now at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @c_barsch

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 15, 2021. May be an image of food and indoor.

node.text: Summer tomatoes are divine, so why not enjoy that flavor year-round? As soon as those juicy, ripe tomatoes hit the market, make a batch (or three) of @chefcortneyburns’ Tomato Brown Butter. This recipe transforms tomatoes into a fragrant, deeply savory, and slightly sweet sauce. Drizzle it over roasted veggies, grain bowls, or even pastas. Freeze it in ice cube trays to enjoy summer flavors all year. Head over to the link in bio to bookmark the recipe. Photo and Food Styling @j_deleo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 14, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: “Basil and pineapple combine in some of my absolute favorite cocktails,” says Kelly Senyei (@justataste). With those flavors in mind, she's turned a wintertime favorite into a summer delight by punching up the rice with sweet-tart pineapple juice and aromatic fresh herbs—an inspired take on a classic that's still simple enough to make on a weeknight. Finish it off with buttery seared scallops and you’re good to go. Get the recipe at the link in bio. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @c_barsch

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by epicurious on July 14, 2021. May be an image of food.

node.text: Pasta is an ingredient for all seasons. For a filling summer meal, cold noodles are perfect for cooling down on hot days. And what picnic or cookout would be complete without a well-dressed, veggie-packed pasta salad? Epi editors have put together 35 of our favorite pasta salad recipes—just click the link in bio to get started. Photo @j_deleo, Food Styling @acstockwell
